<br>
I keep thinking, what of all the people who simply need to see to believe?  Who if Jesus would physically reveal Himself, that they would believe?  Like Thomas.  Thomas absolutely refused to believe the testimony of others who told him that Jesus was alive and risen.  His words were, &quot;Unless I see the nail marks in his hands and put my finger where the nails were, and put my hand into his side, I will not believe it.&quot; (Jn. 20:25b NIV)<br>
<br>
And what happened?  Jesus came just for Thomas, to physically reveal Himself to Thomas so that Thomas alone would believe.  Would Paul have ever believed in Jesus if Jesus had not physically appeared to Him?  No, if so, Jesus wouldn't have physically appeared to Him.  He did what was necessary for Paul (then Saul) to believe.  Two people who refused to believe Jesus was risen and who He said He was and Jesus proved Himself to them physically.  I don't think we generally think of Paul as someone who needed to have physical proof that Jesus was who He said He was.  But it's true.  Paul did not believe on the testimony of others.  Jesus had to physicall prove Himself to Paul.<br>
<br>
Is it fair, then, that Jesus would only give physical proof like that to two people and not to everyone who would need it to believe?  In my heart, I can't believe that God would send someone who truly believes and loves Him but couldn't do so until seeing the Lord physically.<br>
<br>
I don't think the Bible gives us the full picture at all.  And I don't think it tells us much at all about what happens after we die.  We have this very vague understanding that those who don't belong to Jesus will be thrown in the lake of fire and those who belong to Jesus will be with Him forever.  The Lake of Fire is called the second death.  What if that means those who died the first death were given the choice to believe?  What if the second death is reserved only for those who refused God after being given physical proof?<br>
<br>
What if Thomas is an example to us that everyone will be given a chance to believe in Him after being given physical proof?  What if the mainstream Christian thought on this subject is wrong? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
